<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL ROUNDUP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MALIBU: Civic center property owners have appealed a Superior Court decision 
upholding a municipal law restricting development, throwing one of the city's 
most contentious and costly land-use lawsuits back into court. Allan J. Abshez, 
attorney for the Malibu Village Civic Assn., a group of 15 civic center 
landholders who had sued the city to clear the way for a mixed-use residential 
and commercial project, said the state Court of Appeal will hear the case in 
six months to a year. 
</P>
<P>
 The Malibu Village Civic Assn. sued the city last year, charging that the 
city's February, 1993, interim zoning law was invalid because the council did 
not follow proper procedures in adopting it. The association has been concerned 
that the ordinance, which outlaws development, would become part of the city's 
General Plan, which is due for adoption in November. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 MEETINGS NEXT WEEK: 
</P>
<P>
 * Beverly Hills: 7:30 p.m. Tuesday. 450 Crescent Drive. (310) 285-2400. 
</P>
<P>
 * Los Angeles: 10 a.m. Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. 200 N. Spring St. (213) 
485-3126. 
</P>
<P>
 * West Hollywood: 7 p.m. West Hollywood Park Auditorium, 647 N. San Vicente 
Blvd. (310) 854-7460. 
</P>
