<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; PANELS TO ADDRESS IMMIGRATION ISSUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALICIA DI RADO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two local institutions will be hosting upcoming discussions about one of 
Southern California's most controversial topics: immigration. 
</P>
<P>
 Several prominent professors and activists will talk about illegal immigration 
as part of a panel discussion this evening at Cypress College. Another 
discussion at Cal State Fullerton next week will feature an immigration 
attorney, a local Catholic vicar and others. 
</P>
<P>
 The presentation hosted by Cypress College, "Xenophobia and the Scapegoating 
of Undocumented Workers, Families and Students: Chicano and Chicana 
Perspectives," will focus on illegal immigrants and their rights.  
</P>
<P>
 Participants include Rudy Acuna, Cal State Northridge Chicano Studies 
professor; Marta Lopez-Garza, a sociology professor at Occidental College in 
Los Angeles, and Susan Alva, an attorney for the Coalition for Humane Immigrant 
Rights of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Luz Calvo, a Cypress College instructor, said she organized the panel in 
response to the furor over immigration and an ad in the school newspaper 
earlier in the year that read: "Illegal aliens are stealing your education." 
</P>
<P>
 "I wanted to do something to have a more academic and scholarly discussion of 
it," Calvo said. The Cypress College discussion will be from 7 to 9 p.m. in 
Room 216 of the Lecture Hall. 
</P>
<P>
 The second discussion will be Wednesday at Cal State Fullerton. Titled "The 
Human Side of Immigration," it will feature speakers such as Rusty Kennedy of 
the Orange County Human Relations Commission; Gary H. Manulkin, immigration 
attorney; Msgr. Jaime Soto, vicar for the Latino community in the Diocese of 
Orange, and Irene Martinez, executive director of the Delhi Community Center in 
Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
 The talk is part of the second annual National Conference Forum on Diversity 
and Pluralism presented by the National Conference of Christians and Jews, 
Orange County region.  
</P>
<P>
 Organizers invite the public to attend the forum at the Titan Pavilion in the 
University Center at 7:30 p.m. ALICIA DI RADO 
</P>
</TEXT>
