<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIDBITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEO SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Frank DePanise, most recently one of the chefs at the Ojai Valley Inn and 
Country Club, took over last week as the main chef of the Shoals Restaurant at 
Ventura's Cliff House Inn. And some major changes are in store. 
</P>
<P>
 "The guy (Thierry Bregeon) who was here before was a little into old-style 
California cuisine," said the 36-year-old DePanise. "I'm doing something a 
little more rustic, a little more ethnic. I worked at Allegro's in Santa 
Barbara and we did Mediterranean things, dishes from Morocco, Spain, Greece, 
Italy, France. I'm going to bring some of that here, I think." 
</P>
<P>
 DePanise, who also worked at Norbert's Restaurant and Brigitte's in Santa 
Barbara, said to expect the menu to continue to change regularly, as it did 
before his arrival. Also expect some of the same standard items to be included 
on it. "There will always be two or three fresh fish and meat dishes, some 
pasta and vegetable dishes," he said. "But I'm going to stay away from heavier 
sauces and creams." 
</P>
<P>
 The Shoals is located at 6602 W. Pacific Coast Highway. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 What happened to former Shoals chef Bregeon? He's now at La Cumbre Country 
Club in Santa Barbara. And as for the Ojai Valley Inn and Country Club, 
restaurant manager Linda Medd said DePanise has not been replaced. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 More than 15,000 people are expected at the three-day "Taste of Ventura 
County" food and wine festival, beginning Friday at Channel Islands Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
 Sixteen restaurants in the county -- including La Dolce Vita, Capistrano's, 
The Whale's Tail, and Yasmeen's -- plus an ice cream shop and the Oxnard 
Farmers' Market, will sell sample-size food servings for $1 to $5. Four 
wineries and the Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf will have booths set up for 
thirst-quenching purposes. 
</P>
<P>
 "People can literally go to six or seven restaurants, depending on how hungry 
they are," said Susan O'Brien, executive director of the Channel Island Harbor 
Assn. of Lessees, the event organizer. "There's a good cross-section -- 
everything from steakhouses, to Indian restaurants, to Greek restaurants." 
</P>
<P>
 Festival hours are 5 to 11 p.m. Friday, noon to 11 p.m. Saturday, and 11 a.m. 
to 8 p.m. Sunday, with musical entertainment throughout. Admission is $6 for 
adults, $3 for military personnel and persons 55 and older, and free for 
children under age 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
